   <TEXT>
   <S PAR='1' RSNT='1' SNO='1'>OUTLINE THREE SPEAKING POEMS</S>
   <S PAR='2' RSNT='1' SNO='2'>IN THE CHURCH MEETINGS</S>
   <S PAR='3' RSNT='1' SNO='3'>FOR THE ORGANIC BUILDING UP</S>
   <S PAR='4' RSNT='1' SNO='4'>OF THE CHURCH AS THE BODY OF CHRIST For the greatest profit in speaking poems in the church meetings, we must be familiar with the crucial poems in our hymnal, Hymns, that contain the rich speaking forth of the divine truths, i.e. the apostles teaching.</S>
   <S PAR='5' RSNT='1' SNO='5'>If we want to know the hymnal, we must spend time in the table of contents and discover the riches.</S>
   <S PAR='6' RSNT='1' SNO='6'>We have to praise the Lord that we have a Bible and also a hymnal with poems composed according to the truths of the Bible.</S>
   <S PAR='7' RSNT='1' SNO='7'>There are hundreds of poems in our hymnal that contain vital points: The blessing, worship, and experience of the Triune God the Father, the Lord Jesus Christ, and the Spirit.</S>
   <S PAR='8' RSNT='1' SNO='8'>The filling of the Spirit inward and outward.</S>
   <S PAR='9' RSNT='1' SNO='9'>The identification with Christ.</S>
   <S PAR='10' RSNT='1' SNO='10'>The experience of Christ.</S>
   <S PAR='11' RSNT='1' SNO='11'>The experience of the cross and the resurrection life.</S>
   <S PAR='12' RSNT='1' SNO='12'>The various aspects of the inner life.</S>
   <S PAR='13' RSNT='1' SNO='13'>Prayer and service.</S>
   <S PAR='14' RSNT='1' SNO='14'>The church and the kingdom.</S>
   <S PAR='15' RSNT='1' SNO='15'>The assurance of salvation.</S>
   <S PAR='16' RSNT='1' SNO='16'>Consecration.</S>
   <S PAR='17' RSNT='1' SNO='17'>Comfort in trials and encouragement.</S>
   <S PAR='18' RSNT='1' SNO='18'>Spiritual warfare.</S>
   <S PAR='19' RSNT='1' SNO='19'>The gospel.</S>
   <S PAR='20' RSNT='1' SNO='20'>The meetings.</S>
   <S PAR='21' RSNT='1' SNO='21'>The hope of glory.</S>
   <S PAR='22' RSNT='1' SNO='22'>The ultimate manifestation.</S>
   <S PAR='23' RSNT='1' SNO='23'>Concerning the poems that we may speak in the church meetings: We should know the crucial points of the contents of the hymns.</S>
   <S PAR='24' RSNT='1' SNO='24'>We should care for the standard of the hymns: We can know the standard by sensing the hymns.</S>
   <S PAR='25' RSNT='1' SNO='25'>The sensation of a hymn is based upon the thought in the hymn.</S>
   <S PAR='26' RSNT='1' SNO='26'>The sensation of a hymn also refers to its taste.</S>
   <S PAR='27' RSNT='1' SNO='27'>Two examples of the standard of the hymns are as follows: Hymns, #19 not so full of revelation, low and #18 full of revelation, high .</S>
   <S PAR='28' RSNT='1' SNO='28'>Hymns, #70 low in life, truth, experience, and revelation , #154 a higher standard , and #152 the highest standard .</S>
   <S PAR='29' RSNT='1' SNO='29'>We should discern the wording of the hymns.</S>
   <S PAR='30' RSNT='1' SNO='30'>A hymn must have the proper thought.</S>
   <S PAR='31' RSNT='1' SNO='31'>A hymn must have the proper poetic wording to take care of the rhyme and rhythm.</S>
   <S PAR='32' RSNT='1' SNO='32'>We should know the tune of the hymns; many good hymns can be killed by a poor melody.</S>
   <S PAR='33' RSNT='1' SNO='33'>The practice of speaking the poems see XI : Take the words of the hymn as your own words and speak them forth.</S>
   <S PAR='34' RSNT='1' SNO='34'>Function in coordination with the other saints in speaking the hymn to release a full message in mutuality.</S>
   <S PAR='35' RSNT='1' SNO='35'>Each hymn may be considered as a message.</S>
   <S PAR='36' RSNT='1' SNO='36'>Many persons speaking the same hymn speak a complete message for the meeting.</S>
   <S PAR='37' RSNT='1' SNO='37'>Function as a player on the same team playing with one ball the poem being spoken .</S>
   <S PAR='38' RSNT='1' SNO='38'>Keep a good continuation.</S>
   <S PAR='39' RSNT='1' SNO='39'>Speak so that others can catch the ball.</S>
   <S PAR='40' RSNT='1' SNO='40'>Speak with complete clauses, phrases, or expressions so that others can follow.</S>
   <S PAR='41' RSNT='1' SNO='41'>Take care of the proper connection.</S>
   <S PAR='42' RSNT='1' SNO='42'>Keep a good sequence.</S>
   <S PAR='43' RSNT='1' SNO='43'>Connect the points in the poem.</S>
   <S PAR='44' RSNT='1' SNO='44'>Speak in order without discord or confusion .</S>
   <S PAR='45' RSNT='1' SNO='45'>Do not overlap others speaking.</S>
   <S PAR='46' RSNT='1' SNO='46'>Exercise to listen to others speaking as well as caring for your own.</S>
   <S PAR='47' RSNT='1' SNO='47'>Wait on others.</S>
   <S PAR='48' RSNT='1' SNO='48'>Do not fight with one another for an opportunity to speak.</S>
   <S PAR='49' RSNT='1' SNO='49'>Speak with one voice.</S>
   <S PAR='50' RSNT='1' SNO='50'>1 Speaking by yourself.</S>
   <S PAR='51' RSNT='1' SNO='51'>2 Speaking with others.</S>
   <S PAR='52' RSNT='1' SNO='52'>Refrain from scattered speaking.</S>
   <S PAR='53' RSNT='1' SNO='53'>The more clear the speaking is, the more beautiful it is.</S>
   <S PAR='54' RSNT='1' SNO='54'>Speak in a conversational manner without formality.</S>
   <S PAR='55' RSNT='1' SNO='55'>Speak in an informal way free but not wild.</S>
   <S PAR='56' RSNT='1' SNO='56'>Speak by repeating and stressing the crucial words, phrases, and clauses.</S>
   <S PAR='57' RSNT='1' SNO='57'>Speak with different lengths.</S>
   <S PAR='58' RSNT='1' SNO='58'>Use the poem to speak a fresh utterance.</S>
   <S PAR='59' RSNT='1' SNO='59'>Reading is more according to the letter.</S>
   <S PAR='60' RSNT='1' SNO='60'>Speaking may or may not be according to the letter and is free, automatic, and spontaneous.</S>
   <S PAR='61' RSNT='1' SNO='61'>Look at each other when you speak; do not concentrate on your hymn book.</S>
   <S PAR='62' RSNT='1' SNO='62'>John, Did you know....</S>
   <S PAR='63' RSNT='1' SNO='63'>Sue, Our Christ is....</S>
   <S PAR='64' RSNT='1' SNO='64'>Brothers, May we all run the race!</S>
   <S PAR='65' RSNT='1' SNO='65'>Pay full attention to the way of speaking: Not too low without loving the saints ears.</S>
   <S PAR='66' RSNT='1' SNO='66'>Not too loud to hurt the saints ears.</S>
   <S PAR='67' RSNT='1' SNO='67'>Not too slow to exhaust the saints patience.</S>
   <S PAR='68' RSNT='1' SNO='68'>Not too fast to puzzle the saints.</S>
   <S PAR='69' RSNT='1' SNO='69'>Do not do anything to distract others from the flow of the hymn.</S>
   <S PAR='70' RSNT='1' SNO='70'>Do everything in a living way, not in a legal way.</S>
   <S PAR='71' RSNT='1' SNO='71'>Legality brings in death and deadness; we must stay away from the legal deadness.</S>
   <S PAR='72' RSNT='1' SNO='72'>We should try to do everything in a very living way that is flexible and applicable.</S>
   <S PAR='73' RSNT='1' SNO='73'>Practice staying away from routine, deadness, oldness, and tradition.</S>
   <S PAR='74' RSNT='1' SNO='74'>Consider the following illustrations: Speak a whole hymn individually or corporately, and then sing it individually or corporately maybe sing or speak the entire hymn again .</S>
   <S PAR='75' RSNT='1' SNO='75'>Speak a verse of a hymn individually or corporately, and then sing the verse individually or corporately maybe speak or sing the verse again before going to the next verse of the hymn .</S>
   <S PAR='76' RSNT='1' SNO='76'>Sing a hymn individually or corporately, and then speak it individually or corporately.</S>
   <S PAR='77' RSNT='1' SNO='77'>Sing a verse individually or corporately, and then speak it individually or corporately.</S>
   <S PAR='78' RSNT='1' SNO='78'>Speak and sing only one verse of a hymn.</S>
   <S PAR='79' RSNT='1' SNO='79'>Speak and sing only a few verses of a hymn.</S>
   <S PAR='80' RSNT='1' SNO='80'>Sisters speak a verse.</S>
   <S PAR='81' RSNT='1' SNO='81'>Brothers sing a verse.</S>
   <S PAR='82' RSNT='1' SNO='82'>One saint speaks one line, the rest of the brothers and sisters speak the second line, etc. Alternate to speak the whole poem.</S>
   <S PAR='83' RSNT='1' SNO='83'>Proclaim individually or corporately a part of a hymn or the whole hymn as an enlightening message.</S>
   <S PAR='84' RSNT='1' SNO='84'>Etc., etc., etc. There are at least one hundred ways to speak a hymn.</S>
   <S PAR='85' RSNT='1' SNO='85'>Learn not to be redundant speaking the poetry the same way time after time.</S>
   <S PAR='86' RSNT='1' SNO='86'>Learn to also keep the freshness in your speaking by the continuous exercise of your spirit.</S>
   <S PAR='87' RSNT='1' SNO='87'>As in the Psalms, have a Selah sometimes while speaking the poem.</S>
   <S PAR='88' RSNT='1' SNO='88'>Offer a prayer.</S>
   <S PAR='89' RSNT='1' SNO='89'>Speak something briefly from the Word.</S>
   <S PAR='90' RSNT='1' SNO='90'>Explain a little.</S>
   <S PAR='91' RSNT='1' SNO='91'>Share a short testimony.</S>
   <S PAR='92' RSNT='1' SNO='92'>Be free in your spirit to speak, Amen and Hallelujah 1 Cor 14:16.</S>
   <S PAR='93' RSNT='1' SNO='93'>Give a conclusion to the poem sometimes.</S>
   <S PAR='94' RSNT='1' SNO='94'>Stress some of the main points of the poem.</S>
   <S PAR='95' RSNT='1' SNO='95'>Sum up the entire poem.</S>
   <S PAR='96' RSNT='1' SNO='96'>Give a testimony of your experience regarding the content of the poem.</S>
   </TEXT>
